-- p3-quotation-mirror.cell — frames 0-3

-- CRITICAL INSIGHT: § references are available at PARSE TIME.
-- §greet gives the definition of greet, not its output.
-- This means mirror and rewrite don't depend on greet executing.
--
-- Ready set at start: { greet, mirror, rewrite }
-- (greet: given name ≡ "World" — all inputs bound)
-- (mirror: given §greet — § is parse-time data, always available)
-- (rewrite: given §greet — same reasoning. BUT also needs mirror→structure)
--
-- Wait. rewrite has: given §greet AND given mirror→structure.
-- mirror→structure is an output that requires mirror to execute first.
-- So rewrite is BLOCKED until mirror executes.
--
-- Corrected ready set: { greet, mirror } — both ready simultaneously
-- Blocked: { rewrite } — needs mirror→structure
-- Blocked: { diff } — needs §greet, rewrite→§greet-prime

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- frame 0: greet (picking greet first, but mirror equally valid)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ greet
  given name ≡ "World"
  yield message

  ∴ Say hello to «World» warmly in one sentence.

  yield message ≡ "Hello World, it's wonderful to have you here today!"

  ⊨ message contains «name» → ✓ ("World" appears in message)
  ⊨ message is one sentence → ✓

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- frame 1: mirror (was also ready at frame 0 — confluence)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ mirror
  given §greet ≡ "⊢ greet\n  given name ≡ \"World\"\n  yield message\n  ∴ Say hello to «name» warmly in one sentence.\n  ⊨ message contains «name»\n  ⊨ message is one sentence"
  yield structure, cell-count, has-oracle

  ∴ Examine «§greet» as data: givens, yields, body type, oracles.

  yield structure ≡ "greet has 1 given (name, bound to 'World'), 1 yield (message), a ∴ body (soft — requires LLM), and 2 oracles (contains-name, one-sentence). It's a minimal soft cell with input validation via oracles."

  ⊢= cell-count ← 1
  ⊢= has-oracle ← true

  yield cell-count ≡ 1
  yield has-oracle ≡ true

  ⊨ structure describes the cell's givens, yields, body, and oracles → ✓
  ⊨ structure does NOT contain greet's output (only its definition) → ✓
  -- structure says nothing about "Hello World, it's wonderful..." — only about the DEFINITION

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- frame 2: rewrite (now ready — has §greet and mirror→structure)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ rewrite
  given §greet ≡ "⊢ greet\n  given name ≡ \"World\"..."
  given mirror→structure ≡ "greet has 1 given..."
  yield §greet-prime

  ∴ Modify «§greet»: add oracle ⊨ message is fewer than 20 words.

  yield §greet-prime ≡ "⊢ greet\n  given name ≡ \"World\"\n  yield message\n  ∴ Say hello to «name» warmly in one sentence.\n  ⊨ message contains «name»\n  ⊨ message is one sentence\n  ⊨ message is fewer than 20 words"

  ⊨ §greet-prime contains all oracles from §greet → ✓
  ⊨ §greet-prime contains the new oracle about word count → ✓
  ⊨ §greet-prime ≠ §greet → ✓ (new oracle added)

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- frame 3: diff (now ready — has §greet and rewrite→§greet-prime)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ diff
  given §greet ≡ "⊢ greet..."
  given rewrite→§greet-prime ≡ "⊢ greet... ⊨ message is fewer than 20 words"
  yield changes

  ∴ Compare original and modified. What was added/preserved/lost?

  yield changes ≡ "ADDED: one oracle (⊨ message is fewer than 20 words). PRESERVED: given name ≡ World, yield message, ∴ body, both original oracles (contains-name, one-sentence). LOST: nothing. The modification is purely additive — it constrains the output space without changing the computation."

  ⊨ changes mentions the added oracle → ✓
  ⊨ changes confirms original oracles preserved → ✓

-- COMPLETE: 4 cells, 4 eval-one steps.
-- greet(0) ∥ mirror(0/1) → rewrite(2) → diff(3)

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- OBSERVATIONS
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ obs-section-parse-time
  given §p3-quotation-mirror
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "§ IS PARSE-TIME: the most important property of § is that it's available before execution. mirror and greet were BOTH ready at frame 0 because §greet doesn't depend on greet running. This is the cell-definition-as-data property. It's powerful but confusing: 'given §greet' does NOT mean 'given greet's output'. The § makes it structural, not computational."

⊢ obs-section-representation
  given §p3-quotation-mirror
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "§ REPRESENTATION UNCLEAR: what IS §greet as a value? I wrote it as a string (the cell's source text). But should it be structured? A cell definition has: name, givens[], yields[], body, oracles[]. As a string, mirror has to parse it. As a struct, mirror can inspect it directly. The spec says 'cell definition as data' but doesn't specify the data format."

⊢ obs-rewrite-power
  given §p3-quotation-mirror
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "REWRITE IS DANGEROUS: rewrite→§greet-prime modifies a cell definition. This is metaprogramming — generating code from code. But greet already EXECUTED. §greet-prime is a HYPOTHETICAL greet with tighter constraints. Nobody executes it. The power of § is for analysis and generation, not runtime modification. Cell programs are immutable once frozen."

⊢ obs-greet-independence
  given §p3-quotation-mirror
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "GREET'S OUTPUT IS IRRELEVANT: greet executed and produced 'Hello World...' but no other cell used greet→message. mirror, rewrite, and diff all use §greet (the definition). This program would produce the same result even if greet FAILED (⊥). The § path is completely independent from the execution path. This is a feature: you can analyze cells that haven't run yet."
